abstract: U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Tuesday came out in support of Arsenal player Mesut Ozil for his criticism of China's treatment of ethnic Uighur Muslims, saying Beijing can censor the team's football games but cannot hide rights violations.
snippet: U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Tuesday came out in support of Arsenal player Mesut Ozil for his criticism of China's treatment of ethnic Uighur Muslims, saying Beijing can censor the team's football games but cannot hide rights violations.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. Secretary of State Mike Pompeo on Tuesday came out in support of Arsenal player Mesut Ozil for his criticism of China's treatment of ethnic Uighur Muslims, saying Beijing can censor the team's football games but cannot hide rights violations.
headline_main: Pompeo Expresses Support for Arsenal Player in Criticism of China's Treatment of Uighurs
headline_print_headline: Pompeo Expresses Support for Arsenal Player in Criticism of China's Treatment of Uighurs

abstract: Germany believes a new U.S. law imposing sanctions on companies building Russia's contested seabed Nord Stream 2 pipeline could affect ongoing construction works off the coast of Denmark, Bild newspaper said, citing a government document.
snippet: Germany believes a new U.S. law imposing sanctions on companies building Russia's contested seabed Nord Stream 2 pipeline could affect ongoing construction works off the coast of Denmark, Bild newspaper said, citing a government document.
lead_paragraph: BERLIN — Germany believes a new U.S. law imposing sanctions on companies building Russia's contested seabed Nord Stream 2 pipeline could affect ongoing construction works off the coast of Denmark, Bild newspaper said, citing a government document.
headline_main: U.S. Sanctions Could Hit Pipeline Building in Danish Waters: Bild
headline_print_headline: U.S. Sanctions Could Hit Pipeline Building in Danish Waters: Bild

abstract: In an irate, six-page letter to Speaker Nancy Pelosi, President Trump denounced the impeachment inquiry in scathing terms, asserting that he had done nothing wrong and that Democrats would pay a political price in 2020.
snippet: In an irate, six-page letter to Speaker Nancy Pelosi, President Trump denounced the impeachment inquiry in scathing terms, asserting that he had done nothing wrong and that Democrats would pay a political price in 2020.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — President Trump on Tuesday angrily denounced the looming House votes to impeach him as a “Star Chamber of partisan persecution” by Democrats, describing the effort to remove him from office as an “attempted coup” that would come back to haunt them at the ballot box next year.

abstract: U.S. Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell on Tuesday appeared to reject a request from the Senate's top Democrat to call new witnesses in the expected impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
snippet: U.S. Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell on Tuesday appeared to reject a request from the Senate's top Democrat to call new witnesses in the expected impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. Senate Republican leader Mitch McConnell on Tuesday appeared to reject a request from the Senate's top Democrat to call new witnesses in the expected impeachment trial of President Donald Trump.
headline_main: McConnell Suggests Senate Will Not Call Witnesses Requested by Democrats in Impeachment Trial
headline_print_headline: McConnell Suggests Senate Will Not Call Witnesses Requested by Democrats in Impeachment Trial

abstract: Negotiators reached a tentative deal to end a labor dispute that threatened this week's Democratic debate, allowing the event bringing together seven top presidential candidates to proceed, a service workers union and Democratic officials said on Tuesday.
snippet: Negotiators reached a tentative deal to end a labor dispute that threatened this week's Democratic debate, allowing the event bringing together seven top presidential candidates to proceed, a service workers union and Democratic officials said on ...
lead_paragraph: INGLEWOOD, Calif. — Negotiators reached a tentative deal to end a labor dispute that threatened this week's Democratic debate, allowing the event bringing together seven top presidential candidates to proceed, a service workers union and Democratic officials said on Tuesday.
headline_main: U.S. Democratic Debate to Proceed After Labor Dispute Settled
headline_print_headline: U.S. Democratic Debate to Proceed After Labor Dispute Settled

abstract: The State Department said Tuesday that recent congressional action to recognize the Armenian genocide does not reflect Trump administration policy.
snippet: The State Department said Tuesday that recent congressional action to recognize the Armenian genocide does not reflect Trump administration policy.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — The State Department said Tuesday that recent congressional action to recognize the Armenian genocide does not reflect Trump administration policy.
headline_main: State Department: Bill Noting Armenian Genocide Isn't Policy
headline_print_headline: State Department: Bill Noting Armenian Genocide Isn't Policy

abstract: Prime Minister Boris Johnson has set a course to take Britain out of the European Union, and negotiate new free trade deals with Brussels and the United States.
snippet: Prime Minister Boris Johnson has set a course to take Britain out of the European Union, and negotiate new free trade deals with Brussels and the United States.
lead_paragraph: LONDON — Prime Minister Boris Johnson has set a course to take Britain out of the European Union, and negotiate new free trade deals with Brussels and the United States.
headline_main: Factbox: Key Milestones on Britain's Road to Brexit, and Beyond
headline_print_headline: Factbox: Key Milestones on Britain's Road to Brexit, and Beyond

abstract: President Donald Trump supports massive U.S. government spending plans hammered out by Congress this week and plans to sign the $1.4 trillion budget bill into law, White House adviser Kellyanne Conway said on Tuesday.

abstract: U.S. industrial production snapped back last month, posting the biggest gain in more than two years, boosted by the end of a strike at General Motors.
snippet: U.S. industrial production snapped back last month, posting the biggest gain in more than two years, boosted by the end of a strike at General Motors.
lead_paragraph: WASHINGTON — U.S. industrial production snapped back last month, posting the biggest gain in more than two years, boosted by the end of a strike at General Motors.
headline_main: US Industrial Production Snaps Back, Rises 1.1% in November
headline_print_headline: US Industrial Production Snaps Back, Rises 1.1% in November
